            "> African inequality</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/african-wealth-gap-rich-vs-poor.jpg" alt="A fraction of the African population still enjoys the lionâ€™s share of the spoils while the rest struggle to make ends meet" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #a9a7af">
            <i> A fraction of the African population still enjoys the lionâ€™s share of the spoils while the rest struggle to make ends meet. Credits: Anders Pettersson/Getty Images</i>
          </p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
           <strong>The what:</strong> The four richest Africans hold $57.4B in wealth - more than half the continentâ€™s population combined. Over the past five years, African billionaires have seen a 56% increase in their wealth, and currently control nearly $4T. There is also a wide gender wealth gap where men hold three times more wealth than women (<a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-11-jul-25-spotlight-h1-1-the-report" target="_blank">the report</a>). 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
           <strong>The reason:</strong> Africaâ€™s tax structures are nearly three times less effective than the global average at redistributing wealth. Reliance on consumption taxes like VAT (which applies to basic goods and services) forces the poor to spend more on essentials, while budget cuts reduce availability to healthcare and education. Imposing a modest 1% tax on the wealth and 10% on the revenue of the richest could raise $66B each year. 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
          <strong> The challenge:</strong> Political exclusion plays a key role in the cycle of inequality. High entry fees demanded by political parties, along with common vote-buying practices, effectively keep the poor from running for elections. As a result, the wealthy control government decisions and protect their own interests.
          </p>
       
        </mj-text>
