          <h2 style="font-size: 24px; line-height: 1.2; font-weight: 500">Gaza infighting </h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 18px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>Summary: A recent Palestinian militia in Gaza is challenging Hamas rule, alleging Israeli backing. </strong>
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The what:</strong> A 300-member Palestinian militia, known as <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-11-jul-25-spotlight-h2-2-popular-forces" target="_blank">Popular Forces</a>, has emerged in Gaza to challenge Hamas rule. They operate in eastern Rafah under the leadership of <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-11-jul-25-spotlight-h2-3-yasser-abu-shabab" target="_blank">Yasser Abu Shabab</a> and are alleged to protect humanitarian aid from corruption and looting. Their leader asserts his group is coordinating with the Israeli army in Rafah.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The reaction:</strong> Hamas has responded with assassinations of Popular Forces members. They have also denied allegations of war profiteering and the theft of humanitarian aid. A Hamas-run court in Gaza has ordered Abu Shabab to <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-11-jul-25-spotlight-h2-4-surrender" target="_blank">surrender</a> for a hearing on charges of treason, collaborating with hostile entities, and forming an armed gang. 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
           <strong>The big picture:</strong> Israel might take advantage of this group as a tool to undermine Hamas. A broader coalition, including the Palestinian Authority (PA), Egypt, the UAE, and the US, is also reportedly exploring alternatives to Hamas rule. Still, experts dismiss the Popular Forces, citing their leaderâ€™s restricted local support.
          </p>
        </mj-text>
