        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 18px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>Summary: African influencers are spreading misinformation, which could impact the upcoming elections.  </strong>
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The what:</strong> There is a broad trend of disinformation in West Africa. A recent example is the May 19 assertions of a <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-11-jul-25-analysis-h1-5-false-coup" target="_blank">false coup</a> in Abidjan, Ivory Coast's largest city, which created confusion and alarm among the population. With presidential elections scheduled for later this year, experts warn that such false assertions may be used to attack the electoral process. 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The who:</strong> The disinformation is believed to be pushed by social media influencers linked to Burkina Faso. They portray Burkina Faso's military leader, Ibrahim TraorÃ©, as a Pan-African hero who is resisting Western influence, while casting doubt on the Ivory Coastâ€™s democratic institutions (<a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-11-jul-25-analysis-h1-6-about-the-pan-african-movement" target="_blank">about the Pan-African movement</a>).
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
           <strong>The background:</strong> Tensions between Burkina Faso and Ivory Coast worsened when TraorÃ© accused his neighbor of harboring militant groups on its territory and backing plots to overthrow his regime. These narratives are currently feeding regional instability and damaging cross-border relations.
          </p>
