            <strong>ðŸ‡ºðŸ‡¸ USA - Sanctions UN expert.</strong> The US sanctioned UN expert Francesca Albanese for accusing Israel of genocide in Gaza. A vocal critic of Israelâ€™s military actions, Albanese recently urged international sanctions and named US companies aiding the war (<a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-11-jul-25-worldwide-7-speech-crackdowns" target="_blank">speech crackdowns</a>).
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5; padding-bottom: 6px">
            <strong>ðŸ‡ªðŸ‡º European Union - Survived no-confidence vote.</strong> Ursula von der Leyen survived a no-confidence vote in the European Parliament. Still, the vote revealed growing dissatisfaction over her rightward shift, EU transparency issues, and policy direction. She remains in office, but tensions within her coalition suggest more political challenges may follow (<a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-11-jul-25-worldwide-8-eu-dissatisfaction" target="_blank">EU dissatisfaction</a>).
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5; padding-bottom: 6px">
            <strong>ðŸ‡±ðŸ‡· Liberia - Compliment from Trump.</strong> During a White House lunch, Trump praised Liberian President Joseph Boakaiâ€™s English skills, seemingly unaware that English is Liberiaâ€™s official language. The moment sparked criticism, as Liberians found Trumpâ€™s comment offensive, with leaders condemning Trumpâ€™s remarks. Meanwhile, the White House justified the remark as a heartfelt compliment (<a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-11-jul-25-worldwide-9-language-drama" target="_blank">language drama</a>).
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5; padding-bottom: 6px">
            <strong>ðŸ‡¨ðŸ‡³ China - Russian requests.</strong> NATO Secretary General Mark Rutte warned that if China attacks Taiwan, Beijing may ask Russia to open a second front against NATO. He emphasized the need to strengthen NATO and Indo-Pacific cooperation to deter such a scenario. With Russia's defense budget surging and ongoing aggression in Ukraine, Rutte urged NATO members to prepare urgently for potential threats in both Europe and Asia (<a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-11-jul-25-worldwide-10-give-and-take" target="_blank">give and take</a>).
          </p>
