              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">How was Liberia founded?</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/african-american-migration-to-africa-1820.jpg" alt="In 1820, 88 African American men, women, and children boarded a ship in New York Harbor intending to create a colony in Africa" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #a9a7af">
            <i>In 1820, 88 African American men, women, and children boarded a ship in the US Harbor intending to create a colony in Africa. Credits: Corbis/Getty Images</i>
          </p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
           <strong>The beginning:</strong> In the early 19th century, the American Colonization Society (ACS) founded Liberia as a <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-11-jul-25-worldwide-h1-12-home-for-freed-african-americans" target="_blank">home for freed African Americans</a>. Starting in 1816, its goal was to resettle formerly enslaved people in Africa. In 1822, with support from the US government, the first settlers arrived on the West African coast. They laid the groundwork for the Republic of Liberia.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
           <strong>The factors:</strong> Liberia's creation came from deep <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-11-jul-25-worldwide-h1-13-racial-and-political-tensions" target="_blank">racial and political tensions</a> in the US. Many white Americans were supportive of this type of colonization to reduce the number of unbound Black people, whom they saw as a threat. Some African Americans viewed colonization as a possibility to escape racism and create a self-governing society. Despite facing local resistance and challenging conditions, settlers gradually expanded and established governance similar to that of the US.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
          <strong>The result:</strong> Liberia declared its independence in 1847, becoming Africa's first republic, reflecting both US ideals and the complexities of its racial policies. To this day, this distinctive origin continues to influence Liberia's national identity and political development. Trumpâ€™s recent comment about the president of Liberiaâ€™s English highlights how little of this shared history is understood.
          </p>
        </mj-text>
